Pantheon Canonical Intermediate

All representations map through an intermediate semantic form.

Example:

CanonicalMeaningObject:

entities: []
relations: []
constraints: []
sequence: []
metadata: {}

semantic_invariant: string
representation_source: string
representation_target: string
loss_budget: string

This becomes the translation bridge.

⸻

Conservation of Meaning

Every transformation must specify:

Preserved
	•	entities
	•	relationships
	•	constraints
	•	ordering
	•	semantic invariant

Allowed to change
	•	syntax
	•	formatting
	•	verbosity
	•	layout

Potentially lost
	•	rhetorical tone
	•	stylistic nuance
	•	comments
	•	implicit assumptions

⸻

Pantheon Law of Representation

Formal statement:

Any representation can be transformed into another representation if their shared semantic invariant can be preserved and the transformation declares its conservation rules.

⸻

Why this matters

This capability removes a huge bottleneck in knowledge systems.

Normally knowledge gets trapped in its original format:
	•	ideas stuck in conversations
	•	diagrams stuck as images
	•	documents stuck as prose
	•	schemas stuck as config
	•	insights stuck as intuition

Pantheon treats those as temporary vessels.

Meaning becomes portable.

